article.headline: Murray beats Nets moments after Van Horn tied it

images.name: Murray_Lamond 020319 inline
images.caption: Lamond Murray is mobbed by teammates after hitting the game-winning shot, but should it have counted?

article.linkText: Cavs stun Nets with controversial 3 at buzzer
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Rod Thorn helped write the NBA rules, spending 14 years as a league executive. On Tuesday night, the president of the New Jersey Nets insisted the referees ruled incorrectly in a 100-97 loss to the Cleveland Cavaliers. Thorn and the Nets believed Lamond Murray's game-winning 3-pointer from the corner should have been waved off. There were only 0.5 seconds left on the clock when Andre Miller inbounded the ball, and Murray was able to catch it and shoot it before the buzzer sounded. "Obviously it was late," Thorn said. "When you catch the ball sideways, it is impossible to do that (score). That is just unbelievable, absolutely unbelievable. It has nothing to do with the clock, it is the referees' decision about when the clock gets turned on." "By the clock he got the ball off, but that is irrelevant," Thorn said. Referees Leon Wood, Joe Forte and Bennie Adams refused to comment. All three wore belt packs that can activate the clock when a button is pushed. Television replays showed Murray releasing the ball before the clock reached zero. "They have the things on, but sometimes you forget," Thorn said. Keith Van Horn had tied the score at 97 with a 3-pointer moments earlier after taking an inbounds pass from Jason Kidd, who scored 30 points but missed a forced jumper over Murray with five seconds to play that would have put the Nets ahead. "Forget that," Van Horn said. "I don't think we were cheated out of a victory. I think we were cheated out of an opportunity to win." Kidd, who also had 10 rebounds and 10 assists for his eighth triple-double this season, had slapped the ball away from Miller with 23 seconds left to set up the attempt. Wesley Person got the rebound of Kidd's miss, was fouled and made two free throws for a 97-94 lead. Zydrunas Ilgauskas scored a season-high 26 points and dominated the fourth quarter. The 7-foot-3 center also had a season-high 14 rebounds and went 14-of-17 on free throws in his best game since returning Dec. 4 from foot surgery that sidelined him nearly a year. "He had the kind of numbers I told him I expect from him next year," Cavs coach John Lucas said. Ilgauskas scored seven points and had a key blocked shot in a 1:52 span to help Cleveland to a 95-92 lead. His three-point play gave the Cavs a 91-90 lead with 3:06 to play. After Van Horn, who scored 27 points, scored on a layup, Ilgauskas made a 10-foot jumper with 2:31 left, blocked a shot by Van Horn 21 seconds later, then scored again on a 10-foot turnaround jumper. "The final play was supposed to go to Z, too," Murray said. "We wanted to throw it to him for a tip, but Kenyon Martin left me to go and double Z and that left me open. "It just felt good," Murray said. "As it got close, I knew it was." Kidd hit a running 12-footer with 33.7 seconds left to pull the Nets to 95-94. Miller had 23 points and 14 assists, and won for the first time in seven career head-to-head matchups with Kidd. Kidd took over in the second quarter, scoring 11 points in a 4:03 span to help the Nets turn a 30-26 deficit into a 41-38 lead. He had 19 points, seven rebounds and six assists before the break. Miller had 13 points and 11 assists in the first half, which ended in a 52-52 tie. Afterward, Miller left toting a birthday cake. "I'll remember this game and remember this birthday for sure," he said of turning 26. Game notes
Nets G Lucious Harris missed the game with a broken bone in the right side of his face, sustained Sunday against Memphis. ... Cavs F Tyrone Hill was sidelined with a severe sinus infection and will not be with the team in Boston on Wednesday. ... Martin returned after a one-game NBA suspension because of a flagrant foul Friday against Miami's Jim Jackson. ... Kidd also had a triple-double the last time the teams met in Cleveland on Dec. 26.
